00:00:00.440 --> 00:00:03.570
The whole process of natural
selection is to some degree

00:00:03.570 --> 00:00:06.690
dependent on the idea of
variation, that within any

00:00:06.690 --> 00:00:11.450
population of a species, you
have some genetic variation.

00:00:11.450 --> 00:00:15.630
So, for example, let's say I
have a bunch of-- well, this

00:00:15.630 --> 00:00:19.500
is a circle species, and one guy
is that color, and then I

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:22.960
got a bunch more, maybe some
are that color-- oh, that's

00:00:22.960 --> 00:00:26.080
the same color-- that one, and
that one, and that one.

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:28.630
And for whatever reason,
sometimes there are no

00:00:28.630 --> 00:00:32.030
environmental factors that will
predispose one of these

00:00:32.030 --> 00:00:34.800
guys to be able to survive and
reproduce over the other, but

00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:36.530
every now and then, there might
be some environmental

00:00:36.530 --> 00:00:40.620
factor, and it makes maybe, all
of a sudden, this guy more

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:42.090
fit to reproduce.

00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:45.170
And so for whatever reason, this
guy is able to reproduce

00:00:45.170 --> 00:00:49.820
more frequently and these
guys less frequently.

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:53.140
And some of them get killed,
or whatever, or eaten by

00:00:53.140 --> 00:00:56.460
birds, or whatever, or they're
just not able to reproduce for

00:00:56.460 --> 00:00:59.070
whatever reason, and then maybe
these guys are something

00:00:59.070 --> 00:00:59.860
in between.

00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:03.960
So over time, the frequency of
the different traits you see

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:05.400
in this population
will change.

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:07.710
And if they are drastic enough,
maybe these guys start

00:01:07.710 --> 00:01:10.910
becoming dominant and start not
liking these guys, because

00:01:10.910 --> 00:01:12.330
they're so different
or whatever else.

00:01:12.330 --> 00:01:14.110
We could see a lot of
different reasons.

00:01:14.110 --> 00:01:16.460
This could eventually turn
into a different species.

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:21.760
Now, the obvious question is
what leads to this variation?

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:27.520
In a population what leads to
this-- in fact, even in our

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:30.710
population, what leads to one
person having dirty blonde

00:01:30.710 --> 00:01:33.490
hair, one person having brown
hair, one person having black

00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:38.630
hair, and we have the spectrum
of skin complexions and

00:01:38.630 --> 00:01:40.590
heights is pretty
much infinite.

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:41.900
What causes that?

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:44.930
And then one thing that I kind
of point to, we talked about

00:01:44.930 --> 00:01:47.500
this a little bit in
the DNA video, is

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:49.440
this notion of mutations.

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:52.310
DNA, we learned, is just a
sequence of these bases.

00:01:52.310 --> 00:01:56.430
So adenine, guanine, let's say
I've got some thymine going.

00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:58.990
I have some more adenine,
some cytosine.

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:01.780
And that these code, if you have
enough of these in a row,

00:02:01.780 --> 00:02:04.030
maybe you have a few hundred
or a few thousand of these,

00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:06.720
these code for proteins or
they code for things that

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:10.020
control other proteins,
but maybe you have a

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:11.770
change in one of them.

00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:14.330
Maybe this cytosine for whatever
reason becomes a

00:02:14.330 --> 00:02:18.270
guanine randomly, or maybe these
got deleted, and that

00:02:18.270 --> 00:02:19.820
would change the DNA.

00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:23.150
But you could imagine, if I
went to someone's computer

00:02:23.150 --> 00:02:26.220
code and just randomly started
changing letters and randomly

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:29.480
started inserting letters
without really knowing what

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:31.790
I'm doing, most of the time,
I'm going to break the

00:02:31.790 --> 00:02:33.060
computer program.

00:02:33.060 --> 00:02:35.800
Most of the time, the great
majority of the time, this is

00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:37.050
going to go nowhere.

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:41.390
It'll either do nothing, for
example, if I go into

00:02:41.390 --> 00:02:43.240
someone's computer program and
if I just add a couple of

00:02:43.240 --> 00:02:45.190
spaces or something, that might
not change the computer

00:02:45.190 --> 00:02:47.200
program, but if I start getting
rid of semicolons and

00:02:47.200 --> 00:02:49.610
start changing numbers and all
that, it'll probably make the

00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:50.840
computer program break.

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:53.050
So it'll either do nothing or
it'll actually kill the

00:02:53.050 --> 00:02:55.600
organisms most of the time.

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:59.730
Mutations: sometimes, they might
make the actual cell

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:03.060
kind of run amok, and we'll do a
whole maybe series of videos

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:06.920
on cancer, and that itself
obviously would hurt the

00:03:06.920 --> 00:03:09.840
organism as well as a whole,
although if it occurs after

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:12.500
the organism has reproduced, it
might not be something that

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:14.750
selects against the organism
and it also

00:03:14.750 --> 00:03:15.930
wouldn't be passed on.

00:03:15.930 --> 00:03:17.790
But anyway, I won't go
detailed into that.

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:21.470
But the whole point is that
mutations don't seem to be a

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:23.470
satisfying source
of variation.

00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:26.350
They could be a source or kind
of contribute on the margin,

00:03:26.350 --> 00:03:29.910
but there must be something more
profound than mutations

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:32.970
that's creating the diversity
even within, or maybe I should

00:03:32.970 --> 00:03:36.280
call it the variation, even
within a population.

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:38.800
And the answer here is
really it's kind of

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:39.710
right in front of us.

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:43.300
It really addresses kind of one
of the most fundamental

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:46.260
things about biology, and it's
so fundamental that a lot of

00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:49.790
people never even question
why it is the way it is.

00:03:49.790 --> 00:03:51.910
And that is sexual
reproduction.

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:02.670
And when I mean sexual
reproduction, it's this notion

00:04:02.670 --> 00:04:07.870
that you have, and pretty much
if you look at all organisms

00:04:07.870 --> 00:04:10.680
that have nucleuses-- and we
call those eukaroytes.

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:14.780
Maybe I'll do a whole video on
eukaryotes versus prokaryotes,

00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:18.050
but it's the notion that if you
look universally all the

00:04:18.050 --> 00:04:20.190
way from plants-- not
universally, but if you look

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:23.640
at cells that have nucleuses,
they almost universally have

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:29.640
this phenomenon that you have
males and you have females.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:33.510
In some organisms, an organism
can be both a male and a

00:04:33.510 --> 00:04:39.920
female, but the common idea
here is that all organisms

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:42.530
kind of produce versions of
their genetic material that

00:04:42.530 --> 00:04:44.960
mix with other organisms'
version of

00:04:44.960 --> 00:04:46.140
their genetic material.

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:49.410
If mutations were the only
source of variation, then I

00:04:49.410 --> 00:04:53.900
could just bud off other Sals.

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:58.640
Maybe just other Sals would just
bud off from me, and then

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:01.550
randomly one Sal might be a
little bit different and

00:05:01.550 --> 00:05:02.320
whatever else.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:04.630
But that would, as we already
talked about, most of the

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:06.730
time, we would have very little
change, very little

00:05:06.730 --> 00:05:09.500
variation, and whatever
variation does occur because

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:14.160
of any kind of noise being
introduced into this kind of

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:17.650
budding process where I just
replicate myself identically,

00:05:17.650 --> 00:05:19.100
most of the time it'll
be negative.

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:21.790
Most of the time, it'll
break the organism.

00:05:21.790 --> 00:05:24.660
Now, when you have sexual
reproduction, what happens?

00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:27.380
Well, you keep mixing and
matching every possible

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:35.750
combination of DNA in a kind
of species pool of DNA.

