00:09:40.250 --> 00:09:43.700
The version of the gene
here is allele curly.

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:46.610
The gene just says, look, this
is the gene for whether or not

00:09:46.610 --> 00:09:47.600
your hair is curly.

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:50.500
Each version of the gene
is called an allele.

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:52.640
Allele curly.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:56.690
Now, when I got both of these in
my body or in my cells, and

00:09:56.690 --> 00:10:00.040
this is in every cell of my
body, every cell of my body

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:04.080
except for, and we'll talk in
a few seconds about my germ

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:07.330
cells, but every cells other
than the ones that I use for

00:10:07.330 --> 00:10:12.060
reproduction have this complete
set of chromosomes in

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:13.330
it, which I find amazing.

00:10:13.330 --> 00:10:17.690
But only certain chromosomes--
for example, these genes will

00:10:17.690 --> 00:10:20.360
be completely useless in my
fingernails, because all of a

00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:22.760
sudden, the straight and the
curly don't matter that much.

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:23.880
And I'm simplifying.

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:25.980
Maybe they will on some
other dimension.

00:10:25.980 --> 00:10:27.700
But let's say for simplicity,
they won't

00:10:27.700 --> 00:10:28.850
matter in certain places.

00:10:28.850 --> 00:10:32.240
So certain genes are expressed
in certain parts of the body,

00:10:32.240 --> 00:10:35.600
but every one of your body
cells, and we call those

00:10:35.600 --> 00:10:38.980
somatic cells, and we'll
separate those from the sex

00:10:38.980 --> 00:10:45.050
sells or the germs that we'll
talk about later.

00:10:45.050 --> 00:10:48.060
So this is my body cells.

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:50.220
So this is the great majority
of your cells, and this is

00:10:50.220 --> 00:10:52.030
opposed to your germ cells.

00:10:52.030 --> 00:10:54.080
And the germ cells-- I'll just
write it here, just so you get

00:10:54.080 --> 00:10:58.950
a clear-- for a male, that's
the sperm cells, and for

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:01.210
female that's the egg
cells, or the ova.

00:11:04.550 --> 00:11:09.310
But most of my cells have a
complete collection of these,

00:11:09.310 --> 00:11:13.370
and what I want to give you
the idea is that for every

00:11:13.370 --> 00:11:16.200
trait, I essentially have two
versions: one from my mother

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:17.630
and one from my father.

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:21.065
Now, these right here are called
homologous chromosomes.

00:11:25.780 --> 00:11:32.840
What that means is every time
you see this prefix homologous

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:35.850
or if you see like Homo sapiens
or even the word

00:11:35.850 --> 00:11:41.110
homosexual or homogeneous,
it means same, right?

00:11:41.110 --> 00:11:42.640
You see that all the time.

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:46.990
So homologous means that they're
almost the same.

00:11:46.990 --> 00:11:52.230
They're coding for the most part
the same set of genes,

00:11:52.230 --> 00:11:55.100
but they're not identical.

00:11:55.100 --> 00:11:58.950
They actually might code for
slightly different versions of

00:11:58.950 --> 00:11:59.660
the same gene.

00:11:59.660 --> 00:12:02.920
So depending on what versions
I get, what is actually

00:12:02.920 --> 00:12:06.120
expressed for me, so my
genotype-- let me introduce

00:12:06.120 --> 00:12:08.940
another word, and
I'm overwhelming

00:12:08.940 --> 00:12:10.490
you with words here.

00:12:10.490 --> 00:12:17.630
So my genotype is exactly what
alleles I have, what versions

00:12:17.630 --> 00:12:18.170
of the gene.

00:12:18.170 --> 00:12:21.210
So I got like the fifth version
of the curly allele.

00:12:21.210 --> 00:12:23.850
There could be multiple versions
of the curly allele

00:12:23.850 --> 00:12:25.490
in our gene pool.

00:12:25.490 --> 00:12:27.820
And maybe I got some version
of the straight allele.

00:12:27.820 --> 00:12:29.980
That is my genotype.

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:36.170
My phenotype is what my hair
really looks like.

00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:39.720
So, for example, two people
could have different genotypes

00:12:39.720 --> 00:12:42.880
with the same-- they might
code for hair that looks

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:44.560
pretty much the same,
so it might have a

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:47.870
very similar phenotype.

00:12:47.870 --> 00:12:48.980
So one phenotype can be

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:50.640
represented by multiple genotypes.

00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:53.690
So that's just one thing to
think about, and we'll talk a

00:12:53.690 --> 00:12:55.780
lot about that in the future,
but I just wanted to introduce

00:12:55.780 --> 00:12:57.380
you to that there.

00:12:57.380 --> 00:13:01.200
Now, I entered this whole
discussion because I wanted to

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:02.430
talk about variation.

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:04.570
So how does variation happen?

00:13:04.570 --> 00:13:09.130
Well, what's going to happen
when I-- well, let

00:13:09.130 --> 00:13:09.640
me put it this way.

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:11.290
What's going to happen
when I reproduce?

00:13:11.290 --> 00:13:13.990
And I have. I have a son.

00:13:13.990 --> 00:13:18.160
Well, my contribution to my son
is going to be a random

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:22.530
collection of half
of these genes.

00:13:22.530 --> 00:13:25.830
For each homologous pair, I'm
either going to contribute the

00:13:25.830 --> 00:13:28.740
one that I got from my mother or
the one that I got from my

00:13:28.740 --> 00:13:30.250
father, right?

00:13:30.250 --> 00:13:37.360
So let's say that the sperm cell
that went on to fertilize

00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:43.440
my wife's egg, let's say it
happened to have that one,

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:45.400
that one, or I could
just pick one from

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:46.830
each of these 23 sets.

00:13:46.830 --> 00:13:49.020
And you say, well, how many
combinations are there?

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:56.240
Well, for every set, I could
pick one of the two homologous

00:13:56.240 --> 00:13:59.550
chromosomes, and I'm going
to do that 23 times.

00:13:59.550 --> 00:14:02.360
2 times 2 times 2, so that's
2 to the twenty third.

00:14:02.360 --> 00:14:09.220
So 2 to the 23 different
versions that I can contribute

00:14:09.220 --> 00:14:12.800
to any son or daughter that I
might have. We'll talk about

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:16.310
how that happens when we talk
about meiosis or mitosis, that

00:14:16.310 --> 00:14:20.660
when I generate my sperm cells,
sperm cells essentially

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:26.590
takes one-- instead of having
23 pairs of chromosomes in

00:14:26.590 --> 00:14:29.540
sperm, you only have
23 chromosomes.

00:14:29.540 --> 00:14:32.760
So, for example, I'll take one
from each of those, and

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:35.030
through the process of meiosis,
which we'll go into,

00:14:35.030 --> 00:14:37.200
I'll generate a bunch
of sperm cells.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:44.740
And each sperm cell will have
one from each of these pairs,

00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:46.440
one version from each
of those pairs.

00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:51.980
So maybe for this chromosome I
get it from my dad, from the

00:14:51.980 --> 00:14:54.370
next chromosome, I get
it from my mom.

00:14:54.370 --> 00:14:56.840
Then I donate a couple more
from-- I should've drawn them

00:14:56.840 --> 00:14:57.820
next to each other.

00:14:57.820 --> 00:14:59.580
I donate a couple more
from my mom.

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:03.540
Then for chromosome number 5,
it comes from my dad, and so

00:15:03.540 --> 00:15:04.200
on and so forth.

00:15:04.200 --> 00:15:06.200
But there's 2 to the
twenty-third combinations

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:08.240
here, because there
are 23 pairs that

00:15:08.240 --> 00:15:09.290
I'm collecting from.

00:15:09.290 --> 00:15:13.530
Now, my wife's egg is going to
have the same situation.

00:15:13.530 --> 00:15:17.600
There are 2 to the 23 different
combinations of DNA

00:15:17.600 --> 00:15:20.730
that she can contribute just
based on which of the

00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:24.590
homologous pairs she
will contribute.

00:15:24.590 --> 00:15:28.390
So the possible combinations
that just one couple can

00:15:28.390 --> 00:15:34.990
produce, and I'm using my life
as an example, but this

00:15:34.990 --> 00:15:35.980
applies to everything.

00:15:35.980 --> 00:15:39.430
This applies to every species
that experiences sexual

00:15:39.430 --> 00:15:41.190
reproduction.

00:15:41.190 --> 00:15:46.280
So if I can give 2 to
twenty-third combinations of

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:50.620
DNA and my wife can give 2 to
the 23 combinations of DNA,

00:15:50.620 --> 00:15:55.240
then we can produce 2 to the
forty-sixth combinations.

00:15:55.240 --> 00:15:58.220
Now, just to give an idea of how
large of a number this is,

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:02.560
this is roughly 12,000 times the
number of human beings on

00:16:02.560 --> 00:16:03.490
the planet today.

00:16:03.490 --> 00:16:07.210
So there's a huge amount of
variation that even one couple

00:16:07.210 --> 00:16:08.270
can produce.

00:16:08.270 --> 00:16:12.260
And if you thought that even
that isn't enough, it turns

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:15.560
out that amongst these
homologous pairs, and we'll

00:16:15.560 --> 00:16:18.510
talk about when this happens in
meiosis, you can actually

00:16:18.510 --> 00:16:20.630
have DNA recombination.

00:16:20.630 --> 00:16:24.450
And all that means is when these
homologous pairs during

00:16:24.450 --> 00:16:27.730
meiosis line up near each other,
you can have this thing

00:16:27.730 --> 00:16:32.340
called crossover, where all of
this DNA here crosses over and

00:16:32.340 --> 00:16:34.430
touches over here, and all
this DNA crosses over and

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:35.200
touches over there.

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:38.550
So all of this goes there and
all of this goes there.

00:16:38.550 --> 00:16:44.010
What you end up with after the
crossover is that one DNA, the

00:16:44.010 --> 00:16:46.980
one that came from my mom, or
that I thought came from my

00:16:46.980 --> 00:16:49.980
mom, now has a chunk that came
from my dad, and the chunk

00:16:49.980 --> 00:16:55.150
that came from my dad, now has a
chunk that came from my mom.

00:16:55.150 --> 00:16:56.700
Let me do that in
the right color.

00:16:56.700 --> 00:16:59.110
It came from my mom like that.

00:16:59.110 --> 00:17:01.980
And so that even increases the
amount of variety even more.

00:17:01.980 --> 00:17:04.329
So you can almost now, instead
of talking about the different

00:17:04.329 --> 00:17:06.140
chromosomes that you're
contributing where the

00:17:06.140 --> 00:17:09.359
chromosomes are each of these
collections of DNA, you're now

00:17:09.359 --> 00:17:11.579
talking about-- you can almost
go to the different

00:17:11.579 --> 00:17:13.700
combinations at the gene level,
and now you can think

00:17:13.700 --> 00:17:17.410
about it in almost infinite
form of variation.

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:20.910
You can think about all of the
variation that might emerge

00:17:20.910 --> 00:17:23.720
when you start mixing and
matching different versions of

00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:25.560
the same gene in a population.

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:27.150
And you don't just
look at one gene.

00:17:27.150 --> 00:17:31.350
I mean, the reality is that
genes by themselves very

00:17:31.350 --> 00:17:35.290
seldom code for a specific-- you
can very seldom look for

00:17:35.290 --> 00:17:38.330
one gene and say, oh, that is
brown hair, or look for one

00:17:38.330 --> 00:17:41.330
gene and say, oh, that's
intelligence, or that is how

00:17:41.330 --> 00:17:42.550
likable someone is.

00:17:42.550 --> 00:17:45.020
It's usually a whole set of
genes interacting in an

00:17:45.020 --> 00:17:46.840
incredibly complicated way.

00:17:46.840 --> 00:17:50.430
You know, hair might be coded
for by this whole set of genes

00:17:50.430 --> 00:17:52.720
on multiple chromosomes and
this might be coded for a

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:54.880
whole set of genes on multiple
chromosomes.

00:17:54.880 --> 00:17:56.630
And so then you can start
thinking about all of the

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:57.690
different combinations.

00:17:57.690 --> 00:17:59.500
And then all of a sudden, maybe
some combination that

00:17:59.500 --> 00:18:02.190
never existed before all of a
sudden emerges, and that's

00:18:02.190 --> 00:18:03.450
very successful.

00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:06.020
But I'll leave you to think
about it because maybe that

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:08.770
combination might be passed on,
or it may not be passed on

00:18:08.770 --> 00:18:10.580
because of this recombination.

00:18:10.580 --> 00:18:12.480
But we'll talk more about
that in the future.

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:15.720
But I wanted to introduce this
idea of sexual reproduction to

00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:21.690
you, because this really is the
main source of variation

00:18:21.690 --> 00:18:24.080
within a population.

00:18:24.080 --> 00:18:26.730
To me, it's kind of a
philosophical idea, because we

00:18:26.730 --> 00:18:31.580
almost take the idea of having
males and females for granted

00:18:31.580 --> 00:18:34.080
because it's this
universal idea.

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:36.400
But I did a little reading on
it, and it turns out that this

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:40.310
actually only emerged about 1.4
billion years ago, that

00:18:40.310 --> 00:18:43.820
this is almost a useful trait,
because once you introduce

00:18:43.820 --> 00:18:48.360
this level of variation, the
natural selection can start--

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:50.300
you can kind of say that when
you have this more powerful

00:18:50.300 --> 00:18:53.910
form of variation than just pure
mutations, and maybe you

00:18:53.910 --> 00:18:56.540
might have some primitive form
of crossover before, but now

00:18:56.540 --> 00:18:59.220
that you have this sexual
reproduction and you have this

00:18:59.220 --> 00:19:01.980
variation, natural selection
can occur in a

00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:03.320
more efficient way.

00:19:03.320 --> 00:19:06.510
So that species that were able
to reproduce and essentially

00:19:06.510 --> 00:19:09.650
recombine their DNA and mix and
match it in this way were

00:19:09.650 --> 00:19:13.060
able to produce more variety and
were able to essentially

00:19:13.060 --> 00:19:15.120
be selected for their
environment in a more

00:19:15.120 --> 00:19:17.740
efficient way so they started
to essentially outnumber the

00:19:17.740 --> 00:19:20.050
ones that couldn't, so it
became a kind of very

00:19:20.050 --> 00:19:21.720
universal trait.

00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:24.760
But you could have imagined a
world, and there are science

00:19:24.760 --> 00:19:27.180
fiction books written about
this, where you have three

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:30.160
genders, where you have gender
one, two, three.

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:31.410
You could have 10 genders.

00:19:31.410 --> 00:19:36.040
It just happens to be that on
Earth, this notion of having

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:39.750
two genders turned out to be a
very efficient and stable way

00:19:39.750 --> 00:19:42.640
of introducing variation
into a population.

00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:44.070
So, hopefully, you found
that interesting.

